# Angular Material Server-Side Sorting Implementation Guide

## CRITICAL ARCHITECTURE PRINCIPLES

⚠️ **STOP**: You **MUST** understand these fundamental principles before implementing server-side sorting:

### 1. ViewChild Availability is CRITICAL

**⚠️ CRITICAL**: ViewChild must be available for reactive patterns to work.

- **NEVER** conditionally render tables with `*ngIf` based on data length
- **ALWAYS** render table structure so ViewChild is available
- **ALWAYS** check ViewChild availability before initializing reactive patterns

**Chicken-and-Egg Problem to AVOID**:
```html
<!-- PROHIBITED - Creates chicken-and-egg problem -->
<mat-table [dataSource]="data" matSort *ngIf="data.length > 0">
  <!-- Table never renders if data is empty -->
  <!-- ViewChild never available if table never renders -->
  <!-- Reactive pattern never initializes if ViewChild not available -->
  <!-- Data never loads if reactive pattern never initializes -->
</mat-table>
```

**Correct Implementation**:
```html
<!-- REQUIRED - Always render table structure -->
<mat-table [dataSource]="data" matSort>
  <!-- Table columns -->
  <mat-header-row *matHeaderRowDef="columns"></mat-header-row>
  <mat-row *matRowDef="let row; columns: columns;"></mat-row>
  
  <!-- Empty state inside table -->
  <div *ngIf="!loading && data.length === 0" class="empty-state-in-table">
    <mat-icon>info</mat-icon>
    <p>No data found</p>
  </div>
</mat-table>
```

### 2. Angular Lifecycle Coordination

**ALWAYS coordinate between ngOnInit and ngAfterViewInit**:
- `ngOnInit()`: Handle async operations (permissions, initial data)
- `ngAfterViewInit()`: Initialize reactive patterns when ViewChild is available
- Use coordination flags to ensure proper timing

**Required Pattern**:
```typescript
export class TableComponent implements OnInit, AfterViewInit {
  @ViewChild(MatSort) sort!: MatSort;
  
  private shouldInitializeReactivePattern = false;
  private reactivePatternInitialized = false;
  hasPermission = false;

  ngOnInit(): void {
    // Handle async operations
    this.checkPermissions().then(() => {
      this.hasPermission = true;
      this.shouldInitializeReactivePattern = true;
      
      // Initialize if ViewChild is already available
      if (this.sort) {
        this.initializeReactivePattern();
      }
    });
  }

  ngAfterViewInit(): void {
    // Initialize reactive pattern if permissions are ready
    if (this.shouldInitializeReactivePattern && !this.reactivePatternInitialized) {
      this.initializeReactivePattern();
    }
  }

  private initializeReactivePattern(): void {
    // Guard against multiple initialization
    if (this.reactivePatternInitialized || !this.sort || !this.hasPermission) {
      return;
    }
    
    this.reactivePatternInitialized = true;
    // Setup reactive pattern
  }
}
```

## REACTIVE PATTERN IMPLEMENTATION

### 1. Industry-Standard RxJS Pattern

**ALWAYS use the proven RxJS merge() pattern**:

```typescript
import { merge } from 'rxjs';
import { startWith, switchMap, debounceTime } from 'rxjs/operators';

private initializeReactivePattern(): void {
  // Combine all user interaction streams
  merge(
    this.sort.sortChange,
    this.filterForm.valueChanges.pipe(debounceTime(300))
  )
  .pipe(
    startWith({}), // Trigger initial load
    switchMap(() => {
      // Cancel previous requests automatically
      return this.loadDataFromServer();
    })
  )
  .subscribe({
    next: (data) => {
      this.dataSource = data.items;
      this.totalCount = data.total;
      this.loading = false;
    },
    error: (error) => {
      console.error('Data loading error:', error);
      this.loading = false;
    }
  });
}
```

### 2. Server-Side API Requirements

**Backend must support these parameters**:
- `sortBy`: Column name to sort by
- `sortDirection`: 'asc' or 'desc'
- `page`: Page number (0-based or 1-based)
- `pageSize`: Number of items per page
- Filter parameters as needed

**API Response Format**:
```typescript
interface ServerResponse<T> {
  items: T[];
  total: number;
  page: number;
  pageSize: number;
}
```

### 3. Field Mapping for Sort Headers

**ALWAYS map frontend column names to backend field names**:

```typescript
private getSortField(sortHeaderId: string): string {
  const fieldMapping: { [key: string]: string } = {
    'timestamp': 'createdAt',
    'details': 'failureReason',
    'email': 'email',
    'ipAddress': 'ipAddress',
    'status': 'status'
  };
  
  return fieldMapping[sortHeaderId] || sortHeaderId;
}

private loadDataFromServer(): Observable<ServerResponse<any>> {
  const params = {
    sortBy: this.getSortField(this.sort.active),
    sortDirection: this.sort.direction || 'desc',
    page: this.currentPage,
    pageSize: this.pageSize,
    ...this.getFilterParams()
  };
  
  return this.dataService.getData(params);
}
```

## TEMPLATE IMPLEMENTATION

### 1. Required Mat-Table Structure

```html
<!-- Loading indicator -->
<div *ngIf="loading" class="loading-placeholder">
  <mat-spinner diameter="40"></mat-spinner>
  <span>Loading data...</span>
</div>

<!-- Always render table structure -->
<mat-table [dataSource]="dataSource" matSort>
  <!-- Define columns with proper sort headers -->
  <ng-container matColumnDef="timestamp">
    <mat-header-cell *matHeaderCellDef mat-sort-header="createdAt">
      Timestamp
    </mat-header-cell>
    <mat-cell *matCellDef="let item">
      {{ item.createdAt | date:'medium' }}
    </mat-cell>
  </ng-container>
  
  <ng-container matColumnDef="email">
    <mat-header-cell *matHeaderCellDef mat-sort-header>
      Email
    </mat-header-cell>
    <mat-cell *matCellDef="let item">
      {{ item.email }}
    </mat-cell>
  </ng-container>
  
  <!-- More columns... -->
  
  <mat-header-row *matHeaderRowDef="displayedColumns"></mat-header-row>
  <mat-row *matRowDef="let row; columns: displayedColumns;"></mat-row>
  
  <!-- Empty state inside table -->
  <div *ngIf="!loading && dataSource.length === 0" class="empty-state-in-table">
    <mat-icon class="empty-icon">inbox</mat-icon>
    <p>No data available</p>
  </div>
</mat-table>

<!-- Pagination -->
<mat-paginator
  *ngIf="!loading && totalCount > 0"
  [length]="totalCount"
  [pageSize]="pageSize"
  [pageSizeOptions]="[5, 10, 25, 50]"
  (page)="onPageChange($event)">
</mat-paginator>
```

### 2. Sort Header Configuration

**Use mat-sort-header with proper field mapping**:
- `mat-sort-header` without value uses column def name
- `mat-sort-header="fieldName"` maps to specific backend field
- Handle field name differences between frontend and backend

## PROHIBITED PRACTICES - ALWAYS AVOID

⚠️ **WARNING: NEVER use these anti-patterns:**

### 1. **NEVER** conditionally render tables based on data
```html
<!-- PROHIBITED - Creates ViewChild unavailability -->
<mat-table *ngIf="data.length > 0" [dataSource]="data" matSort>
```

### 2. **NEVER** use recursive retry logic for ViewChild
```typescript
/* PROHIBITED - Creates infinite loops */
private initializeReactivePattern(): void {
  if (!this.sort) {
    setTimeout(() => this.initializeReactivePattern(), 100); // INFINITE LOOP
    return;
  }
}
```

### 3. **NEVER** start reactive patterns before ViewChild is ready
```typescript
/* PROHIBITED - Race condition */
ngOnInit(): void {
  // ViewChild not available yet
  this.initializeReactivePattern(); // WILL FAIL
}
```

### 4. **NEVER** ignore permission checks in reactive patterns
```typescript
/* PROHIBITED - Security issue */
private initializeReactivePattern(): void {
  // Missing permission check
  merge(this.sort.sortChange)
    .pipe(switchMap(() => this.loadData())) // Unauthorized access
    .subscribe();
}
```

### 5. **NEVER** use client-side sorting for large datasets
```typescript
/* PROHIBITED - Performance issue */
this.dataSource.sort = this.sort; // Client-side sorting
```

## DEBUGGING SERVER-SIDE SORTING

### 1. Investigation Checklist

**Before debugging, verify these prerequisites**:
- [ ] Table structure always renders (no conditional `*ngIf`)
- [ ] ViewChild is available (`this.sort` is defined)
- [ ] Permission check passes
- [ ] Reactive pattern initializes
- [ ] Sort events fire when clicking headers
- [ ] API calls include correct sort parameters
- [ ] Backend returns sorted data

### 2. Debug Console Logging

**Add comprehensive debug logging**:
```typescript
private initializeReactivePattern(): void {
  console.log('[DEBUG] initializeReactivePattern called', {
    hasPermission: this.hasPermission,
    sortAvailable: !!this.sort,
    alreadyInitialized: this.reactivePatternInitialized
  });
  
  if (!this.hasPermission || !this.sort || this.reactivePatternInitialized) {
    console.log('[DEBUG] Prerequisites not met', {
      hasPermission: this.hasPermission,
      sortAvailable: !!this.sort
    });
    return;
  }
  
  // Setup reactive pattern with logging
  merge(this.sort.sortChange)
    .pipe(
      tap(() => console.log('[DEBUG] Sort changed:', this.sort.active, this.sort.direction)),
      switchMap(() => {
        console.log('[DEBUG] Loading data with sort:', {
          sortBy: this.getSortField(this.sort.active),
          sortDirection: this.sort.direction
        });
        return this.loadDataFromServer();
      })
    )
    .subscribe({
      next: (data) => console.log('[DEBUG] Data loaded:', data.items.length, 'items'),
      error: (error) => console.error('[DEBUG] Loading error:', error)
    });
}
```

### 3. Common Issues and Solutions

1. **Empty Table**: Check ViewChild availability and reactive pattern initialization
2. **Sort Not Working**: Verify sort headers and field mapping
3. **Infinite Loops**: Remove recursive retry logic, use proper lifecycle coordination
4. **Race Conditions**: Coordinate ngOnInit and ngAfterViewInit properly
5. **Permission Issues**: Ensure frontend and backend use same permission names

